<div id="review_2034972484" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2034972484" />
    <a title="Vikrama Dhiman" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/63027503-vikrama-dhiman"><img alt="Vikrama Dhiman" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1523840573p2/63027503.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2034972484?book_show_action=true">Sep 06, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Vikrama Dhiman" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Vikrama Dhiman" href="/user/show/63027503-vikrama-dhiman">Vikrama Dhiman</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="ebook 9781845137540" href="/book/show/19291563-banker-to-the-poor">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2034972484" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4475952762518120557">Finally, also read Banker to the Poor. And, haven’t been able to get over it. What a life, what an institution and what a book! Muhammad Yunus left his life in America in the 1970s and moved to Bangladesh and set a model of how poverty can be lifted through free market banking initiative called Grameen Bank. Not a single chapter or a page in the book is without meaning. The thing that struck me the most (and I did not know beforehand) was that the Grameen Bank is an ultimate feminist bank - it l</span>
  <span id="freeText4475952762518120557" style="display:none">Finally, also read Banker to the Poor. And, haven’t been able to get over it. What a life, what an institution and what a book! Muhammad Yunus left his life in America in the 1970s and moved to Bangladesh and set a model of how poverty can be lifted through free market banking initiative called Grameen Bank. Not a single chapter or a page in the book is without meaning. The thing that struck me the most (and I did not know beforehand) was that the Grameen Bank is an ultimate feminist bank - it largely lends only to the poor ‘women’. The most poignant line in the book was - *‘If one of the family members has to starve, it is an unwritten law that it has to be the mother.’* Now, lending to women was not from some altruistic thoughts but experiments run in the early days, where they found that lending to women produced better results for the entire family. The book has story after story of poor women escaping poverty by taking loans of less than $10. _In one case a woman said, ‘‘All my life I was told I was no good, that I brought only misery to my parents because I was a woman and my family could not pay for my dowry. Many times I heard my mother say she should have killed me at birth. I did not feel I was worthy of a loan, or that I could ever repay it.’_ Grameen Bank turned all this around - if men needed the loan, they had to transfer the land ownership to their wife, and the loan would be given to the wife, They also fought religious dictates, militancy, and corrupt officials. The book also brings about the awful lending policies of most banks (which continue to date) and global corporations like World Bank. Banks lend to the rich big amount who default on most payments. And, despite a 90%+ return from the poor, they don’t lend to the poor without the collateral. Book also showcases how World Bank is one of the biggest sources of corruption in the developing countries. Yet, despite this, Muhammad Yunus is not a socialist. He advocates a ‘truly’ free market banking and financial sector that allows self-employed poor to access small loans, Yunus also asks the nations to measure their progress by per capita income of the bottom 25% of the population and not overall per-capita. This is a book is of hope. It shows that lifting people out of poverty is doable and how to do this through free market principles. Yunus also had help from his students, family, bank officials, and even some government officials - there are good people around us. Can’t recommend the book enough. Read to find out how small loans to the poor work, are they guaranteed, should poor go to the bank or the bank go to the poor, why women are the poorest section of the society and also the one that changes an entire generation, and how a group of women can change an entire village, and lift it out of poverty.</span>
  <a data-text-id="4475952762518120557" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

