<span id="freeTextContainer8655877172131975779">I wonder why this book is read by not many people (Based on the number on goodreads). I wonder why this book is not published in many many languages, by many many publishing houses! <br/><br/>The heck is happening? The answer to end poverty for the poor is here (poor people here means those in an inescapable cycle of debt only to have their mouths feed everyday. Needless to say, they dont want to be a burden on the gvm&apos;s budget and our tax money).<br/><br/>People in this book, in Bangladesh, are darn poor. Poverty </span>
  <span id="freeText8655877172131975779" style="display:none">I wonder why this book is read by not many people (Based on the number on goodreads). I wonder why this book is not published in many many languages, by many many publishing houses! <br /><br />The heck is happening? The answer to end poverty for the poor is here (poor people here means those in an inescapable cycle of debt only to have their mouths feed everyday. Needless to say, they dont want to be a burden on the gvm's budget and our tax money).<br /><br />People in this book, in Bangladesh, are darn poor. Poverty rate there in 2000 is 83%, in which 33% living in extreme poverty (World Bank), and have I mentioned these people were living in a country of religious and armed conflict? I know there are places that could be worse than this, but we are trying to focus on the context of the book here. <br /> <br />So to combat poverty, the solution the author proposes and the way he literally has been implementing in his country might not be the same in every country, but his vision in making micro lending available to the poor is universal. One of the problems with the poor, he says, is they are 'afraid' of the bank. Live on a street where there are 5 banks within few walks and a wet market right around the corner, I am sure the vendors there don't go to the bank, at least not one of those five. And to me, if I dont get paid by bank transfer and the need to do all the complicate transactions, I dont think I would ever want a bank account. Feel like the perk of having money in it is excluded for the not-have-a-lot-of-money, at least thats what's happening with my ATM account. <br /><br />So why I am ranting here? I might sound like an optimist saying this, but I do hope there would be many publishing houses in many countries, developed and developing, publish this book. Why? Because there is a poverty problem, and the solution is not complicate.</span>
